---
import CaseStudyLayout from "../../../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro";
import CalloutColumn from "../../../../components/sections/CalloutColumn.astro";
import ContentSection from "../../../../components/sections/ContentSection.astro";
import CalloutBlock from "../../../../components/sections/CalloutBlock.astro";
import InfoCardGrid from "../../../../components/sections/InfoCardGrid.astro";
import MediaSection from "../../../../components/sections/MediaSection.astro";
import MetaGrid from "../../../../components/sections/MetaGrid.astro";
import MetaItem from "../../../../components/sections/MetaItem.astro";
import SectionIntro from "../../../../components/sections/SectionIntro.astro";
import SplitAsideSection from "../../../../components/sections/SplitAsideSection.astro";
import SurfaceCard from "../../../../components/sections/SurfaceCard.astro";
import MicroLabel from "../../../../components/typography/MicroLabel.astro";
import CardTitle from "../../../../components/typography/CardTitle.astro";
import SectionBody from "../../../../components/typography/SectionBody.astro";
import { resolveStaticAssetUrl as asset } from "../../../../lib/assetUrl";

const moreCaseStudies = [
	{
		href: "/design/case-studies/aosp",
		title: "Avast Online Security & Privacy",
		logoSrc: "/favicons/avast.ico",
		logoAlt: "Avast",
		imageSrc: "/images/case-studies/aosp/aosp-hero.jpg",
		imageAlt: "Avast Online Security & Privacy case study preview",
		description:
			"A major redesign of the flagship browser extension with over 10 million users."
	},
	{
		href: "/design/case-studies/trackoff",
		title: "TrackOFF",
		logoSrc: "/favicons/trackoff.png",
		logoAlt: "TrackOFF",
		imageSrc: "/images/case-studies/trackoff/trackoff-hero.jpg",
		imageAlt: "TrackOFF case study preview",
		description:
			"A short story about building a successful product from the ground up and seeing it through to acquisition."
	}
];
---

<CaseStudyLayout
	title="Cookie Manager | Design Case Study | Dmitry Shkaev"
	description="Designing, building, and integrating a new feature in Avast Online Security & Privacy."
	pageTitle="Cookie Manager"
	heroSrc="/images/case-studies/cookie-manager/cookie-manager-hero.jpg"
	heroAlt="Cookie Manager case study hero image"
	moreCaseStudies={moreCaseStudies}
	locale="ru"
>

		<ContentSection title="Executive summary" bodyClass="mt-6">
			<p>
				Building on the successful Avast Online Security &amp; Privacy
				redesign, our team developed a new feature for the company's flagship
				browser extension. This allowed us to expand the initial offering and
				pave a smoother path towards transitioning to the paid model as well
				as an integration with the <a
					href="https://www.avast.com/avast-one"
					target="_blank"
					rel="noreferrer"
						class="text-link text-stone-950"
					>Avast One</a> suite.
			</p>
		</ContentSection>

		<ContentSection
			title="Team"
			class="border-y border-stone-200 pt-10 pb-12"
			bodyClass="mt-6 space-y-8"
		>
				<p>
					A compact cross-functional team carried Cookie Manager from product
					framing through design, research, implementation, and release.
				</p>
				<MetaGrid>
					<div class="lg:col-span-1">
						<div class="space-y-5">
							<MetaItem label="Product owner">
								<p>
									<a
										href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/ron-ward-30432894/"
										target="_blank"
										rel="noreferrer"
										class="text-link text-stone-950"
									>Ron Ward</a>
								</p>
							</MetaItem>
							<MetaItem label="Product designer">
								<p>
									<a
										href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/shkaev/"
										target="_blank"
										rel="noreferrer"
										class="text-link text-stone-950"
									>Dmitry Shkaev</a>
								</p>
							</MetaItem>
							<MetaItem label="Engineering">
								<p>
									<a
										href="https://bit.ly/3WzT3GQ"
										target="_blank"
										rel="noreferrer"
										class="text-link text-stone-950"
									>Jiri Pojezny</a>, <a
										href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/gilyov/"
										target="_blank"
										rel="noreferrer"
										class="text-link text-stone-950"
									>Anton Gilyov</a>
								</p>
							</MetaItem>
						</div>
					</div>
					<div class="lg:col-span-2">
						<div class="space-y-5">
							<MetaItem label="UX research">
								<p>
									<a
										href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/natalie-schinkova/"
										target="_blank"
										rel="noreferrer"
										class="text-link text-stone-950"
									>Natalie Schinkova</a>, <a
										href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/veronikakonecna/"
										target="_blank"
										rel="noreferrer"
										class="text-link text-stone-950"
									>Veronika Konecna</a>
								</p>
							</MetaItem>
							<MetaItem label="UX writing">
								<p>
									<a
										href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/alyyamada/"
										target="_blank"
										rel="noreferrer"
										class="text-link text-stone-950"
									>Alysa Yamada</a>
								</p>
							</MetaItem>
						</div>
					</div>
				</MetaGrid>
		</ContentSection>

		<section class="mt-12 w-full">
			<SectionIntro as="div" class="mt-0" title="Problem statement" />
			<div class="mt-6 grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-3">
				<CalloutColumn title="The acquired product" bodyClass="space-y-4">
					<p>
						In 2021, Avast <a
							href="https://www.i-dont-care-about-cookies.eu/whats-new/acquisition/"
							target="_blank"
							rel="noreferrer"
							class="text-link text-stone-950"
						>purchased</a> a popular browser extension called "I Don't Care
						About Cookies" created by Croatian developer <a
							href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/dkladnik/"
							target="_blank"
							rel="noreferrer"
							class="text-link text-stone-950"
						>Daniel Kladnik</a>. The product already had clear demand: it
						removed cookie consent prompts and let people browse with fewer
						interruptions, which was especially relevant in GDPR-heavy
						markets.
					</p>
				</CalloutColumn>
				<CalloutColumn title="Why it was paused" bodyClass="space-y-4">
					<p>
						The intention was to embed that capability into one of Avast's
						privacy products, initially Avast AntiTrack. But as a paid tool,
						it was not the right environment to unlock broad user value from
						the acquisition. Amid larger internal shifts at Avast, the
						purchased extension was temporarily shelved.
					</p>
				</CalloutColumn>
				<CalloutColumn title="Why AOSP became the fit" bodyClass="space-y-4">
					<p>
						That changed with the <a
							href="/design/case-studies/aosp"
							class="text-link text-stone-950"
						>revival of Avast Online Security &amp; Privacy</a> by the end of
						2021. AOSP had quickly become one of the company's top products
						and was the first place where this acquisition could strengthen
						the core value proposition instead of feeling bolted on.
					</p>
				</CalloutColumn>
			</div>
			<CalloutBlock
				label="My role"
				title="Turning the acquisition into a product feature"
				body="As the designer on Avast Online Security & Privacy, I led the work of shaping that acquisition into a coherent feature within the product."
				class="mt-8"
			>
				<span slot="label-prefix" class="-translate-y-px text-amber-500">
						<svg
							xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
							viewBox="0 0 20 20"
							fill="currentColor"
							class="h-4 w-4"
							aria-hidden="true"
						>
							<path
								fill-rule="evenodd"
								d="M10.868 2.884c-.321-.772-1.415-.772-1.736 0l-1.83 4.401-4.753.381c-.833.067-1.171 1.107-.536 1.651l3.62 3.102-1.106 4.637c-.194.813.691 1.456 1.405 1.02L10 15.591l4.069 2.485c.713.436 1.598-.207 1.404-1.02l-1.106-4.637 3.62-3.102c.635-.544.297-1.584-.536-1.65l-4.752-.382-1.831-4.401Z"
								clip-rule="evenodd"
							></path>
						</svg>
				</span>
			</CalloutBlock>
		</section>

		<MediaSection
			src={asset("/images/case-studies/cookie-manager/cookie-manager-wireframes.jpg")}
			alt="Cookie Manager wireframes"
		/>

		<section class="mt-12 w-full">
			<SectionIntro as="div" class="mt-0" title="Design goals" />
			<InfoCardGrid>
				<SurfaceCard>
					<MicroLabel>Flow</MicroLabel>
					<CardTitle class="mt-4 text-[1.35rem] leading-[1.08] sm:text-[1.5rem]">
						Make browsing feel uninterrupted
					</CardTitle>
					<p class="mt-3 text-[0.98rem] leading-7 text-stone-700 sm:text-base">
						Help people get cookie banners out of the way instead of repeatedly
						breaking their flow.
					</p>
				</SurfaceCard>
				<SurfaceCard>
					<MicroLabel>Complexity</MicroLabel>
					<CardTitle class="mt-4 text-[1.35rem] leading-[1.08] sm:text-[1.5rem]">
						Go beyond the easy cases
					</CardTitle>
					<p class="mt-3 text-[0.98rem] leading-7 text-stone-700 sm:text-base">
						Address multi-option consent flows that the original extension did
						not fully resolve.
					</p>
				</SurfaceCard>
				<SurfaceCard>
					<MicroLabel>Integration</MicroLabel>
					<CardTitle class="mt-4 text-[1.35rem] leading-[1.08] sm:text-[1.5rem]">
						Make it belong in the product
					</CardTitle>
					<p class="mt-3 text-[0.98rem] leading-7 text-stone-700 sm:text-base">
						Integrate the new feature into the recently redesigned framework so
						it felt native in both UX and visual language.
					</p>
				</SurfaceCard>
			</InfoCardGrid>
		</section>

		<section class="mt-12 w-full">
			<SectionIntro as="div" class="mt-0" title="Design process" />
			<SplitAsideSection gridClass="lg:grid lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,3fr)_minmax(0,1fr)] lg:items-stretch lg:gap-10">
				<div slot="main">
					<SectionBody class="mt-0">
						<p>
							Business justification was already in place by the time design
							began, so there was no need for a classic discovery phase. Our
							first task was to decide where this new capability should live
							inside the product. The original extension barely had an
							interface, so we were effectively starting from scratch while
							reusing parts of its backend.
						</p>
					</SectionBody>
					<CalloutBlock
						label="Next steps"
						title="From the first drafts to the user testing"
						body="I produced wireframes covering all key ideas and requirements. We went through a few rounds of internal feedback, and then I moved on to produce hi-fi visuals to run the first external user test."
						class="mt-8"
					>
						<span slot="label-prefix" class="-translate-y-px text-amber-500">
								<svg
									xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
									viewBox="0 0 20 20"
									fill="currentColor"
									class="h-4 w-4"
									aria-hidden="true"
								>
									<path
										fill-rule="evenodd"
										d="M10.868 2.884c-.321-.772-1.415-.772-1.736 0l-1.83 4.401-4.753.381c-.833.067-1.171 1.107-.536 1.651l3.62 3.102-1.106 4.637c-.194.813.691 1.456 1.405 1.02L10 15.591l4.069 2.485c.713.436 1.598-.207 1.404-1.02l-1.106-4.637 3.62-3.102c.635-.544.297-1.584-.536-1.65l-4.752-.382-1.831-4.401Z"
										clip-rule="evenodd"
									></path>
								</svg>
						</span>
					</CalloutBlock>
				</div>
				<div slot="aside">
					<CalloutColumn
						title="The Challenge"
						titleAs="h3"
						titleClass="text-[1.2rem] sm:text-[1.3rem]"
						bodyClass="space-y-4 text-[0.98rem] leading-7 sm:text-base"
					>
						<p>
							Balance user value, usability, in-app visibility, and business
							impact without pulling too much attention away from the core
							features.
						</p>
						<p>
							Early concepts ranged from a simple checkbox to a dedicated area
							in the UI. The richer direction won out, with an on/off toggle,
							value indicators, customization, and whitelisting.
						</p>
					</CalloutColumn>
				</div>
			</SplitAsideSection>
		</section>

		<ContentSection title="Prototype">
				<p>
					After running the high-fidelity screens by the team and receiving
					sign-off from our project owner, I created a prototype in Figma,
					emulating the flow from installing the extension to discovering and
					using the Cookie Manager feature.
				</p>
				<p>
					To prepare for the user interviews, we sourced questions from all
					stakeholders and key team members. The user interviews were
					conducted by my colleagues Natalie and Veronika. I joined one of the
					early calls to see if we were on the right track with gathering
					useful information. They also did a great job of putting together an
					extensive summary of the findings. Still, I watched all the
					recordings later by myself to note the specific observations I was
					looking for.
				</p>
		</ContentSection>

		<MediaSection
			src={asset("/images/case-studies/cookie-manager/cookie-manager-prototype.png")}
			alt="Cookie Manager prototype screens"
		/>

		<ContentSection title="User experience research outcome">
				<p>
					The results were strong and, in some respects, eye-opening. It was
					one of the most useful pieces of qualitative user research I had in
					a while, because of the number of important insights that people
					shared with us. As often happens, some of our previous assumptions
					did not hold up, and some performed really well.
				</p>
				<p>
					For example, initially we adopted a tooltip system from Avast One,
					where people would hover over a question mark icon and read a short
					helper text. This interaction pattern has existed since the earliest
					visual operating systems, so it seemed obvious for the user. In
					reality, only two people out of ten found it, and only one of them
					cared to read the text. Even that person struggled to understand the
					intended message.
				</p>
				<p>
					Overall, the feature was well received, and there were only moderate
					to minor usability issues. We presented the findings summary to the
					team for discussion and prioritization.
				</p>
		</ContentSection>

		<MediaSection
			src={asset("/images/case-studies/cookie-manager/cookie-manager-research.png")}
			alt="Cookie Manager user research findings"
		/>

		<section class="mt-12 w-full">
			<div class="space-y-4 text-base leading-8 text-stone-700 sm:text-lg">
				<p>
					Next, I set out to structure, verify, and implement the feedback we
					had agreed to address.
				</p>
				<p>
					<strong class="font-bold text-stone-950"
						>As a result of this research, we reimagined how we presented
						complex cookie popups and the options provided to the user.</strong
					> Ideally, a second round of qualitative research would have
					followed, but given the tight timeline, we decided to proceed with
					the release, gather quantitative data, and revisit the feature in a
					second phase.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<MediaSection
			src={asset("/images/case-studies/cookie-manager/cookie-manager-handoff.png")}
			alt="Cookie Manager final designs and handoff"
		/>

		<section class="mt-12 w-full">
			<div class="grid gap-4 lg:grid-cols-3">
				<SurfaceCard as="article">
					<CardTitle as="h2" class="text-[1.35rem] leading-tight sm:text-[1.5rem]">
						Handoff
					</CardTitle>
					<p class="mt-3 text-[0.98rem] leading-7 text-stone-700 sm:text-base">
						We had a dedicated team of engineers assigned to the project, so
						our collaboration started as soon as the project kicked off.
						Working together, we were building the feature iteratively and on
						schedule, quickly resolving any issues as they emerged. I was
						pleased with how faithfully the frontend implementation matched
						the design.
					</p>
				</SurfaceCard>

				<SurfaceCard as="article">
					<CardTitle as="h2" class="text-[1.35rem] leading-tight sm:text-[1.5rem]">
						How we measured success
					</CardTitle>
					<p class="mt-3 text-[0.98rem] leading-7 text-stone-700 sm:text-base">
						The OKRs were well-defined: shipping on schedule, improving
						adoption after release, measuring sales impact from
						cross-promotional campaigns, increasing NPS results by a set
						amount, and a few others.
					</p>
				</SurfaceCard>

				<SurfaceCard as="article">
					<CardTitle as="h2" class="text-[1.35rem] leading-tight sm:text-[1.5rem]">
						Results
					</CardTitle>
					<p class="mt-3 text-[0.98rem] leading-7 text-stone-700 sm:text-base">
						We successfully shipped Cookie Manager and launched it alongside
						a marketing campaign. This marked an important milestone in the
						AOSP product roadmap. Over the next few months, adoption and
						engagement rates for Cookie Manager exceeded our expectations.
					</p>
				</SurfaceCard>
			</div>
		</section>

		<ContentSection title="Personal takeaway">
				<p>
					This was a perfect example of end-to-end regular design work in a
					corporate environment, excluding the discovery phase. It might seem
					routine on the surface, but these projects are always unique and
					present their own challenges. In this particular instance, I really
					liked how user research reshaped our design decisions and
					significantly affected the complexity of information presented to
					users.
				</p>
				<p>
					Within a single project I had a chance to come up with a new
					information architecture, create raw concepts, craft prototypes,
					validate our ideas through feedback sessions and research, build
					high-fidelity UI, ship to developers, and work with them to oversee
					the implementation. It really had it all.
				</p>
		</ContentSection>

</CaseStudyLayout>
